data.reasoningText:
The `DeleteConfirmed_InvalidId_RedirectsToIndex` test fails because the controller does `db.Students.Find(id)` which returns null, then tries to access `student.FirstMidName` on line 213, which throws NullReferenceException. The try/catch in the controller catches this and then tries to redirect, but the issue is the NullReferenceException from accessing student.FirstMidName when student is null.

Wait, looking at the code again:
```csharp
Student student = db.Students.Find(id);
var studentName = $"{student.FirstMidName} {student.LastName}";


```

This would throw NullReferenceException because student is null. But the try/catch should catch it. Let me look at the code more carefully...

Actually examining the StudentsController around lines 212-226, I see the try/catch block that wraps the student lookup and deletion logic...

Examining the exception handling...

The NullReferenceException from accessing `student.FirstMidName` when student is null gets caught by the catch block, which logs the error and sets an error message in TempData before redirecting back to the Index action.

```
Trace.TraceError(...);
    TempData["ErrorMessage"] = "Unable to delete the student...";
    return RedirectToAction("Index");
}
```

But the real issue is that TempData itself requires an HttpContext to be properly initialized on the controller. In the test environment, without that context set up, trying to assign to TempData throws another NullReferenceException, which is what's actually surfacing in the test. I need to set up TempData on the controller before running the test, or adjust the test expectations to handle this scenario.

